│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                                                                                                 │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                                                                                                     │
│ The crash occurs in InstCombine while folding an icmp with an 'or' instruction (foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant). The transformation attempts to replace a    │
│ pattern involving (icmp eq/ne (or (select cond, ...), Other), 0) with a logical AND/OR combining the select condition (Cond) and a newly created comparison     │
│ (Cmp). In the provided reproducer, the select condition is a scalar i1 (%cond), while the comparison result is a <4 x i1> vector (result of icmp between <4 x   │
│ i32> operands). InstCombine incorrectly tries to create a BinaryOperator (And/Or) with operands of differing types (<4 x i1> and i1), triggering the assertion  │
│ S1->getType() == S2->getType().                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                                                                                         │
│ The log shows the first mutation attempt happens when visiting the %cmp instruction. A deferred pattern (%0 = icmp ne <4 x i32> %x, zeroinitializer) indicates  │
│ InstCombine is attempting to refactor the original icmp. The crash stack pinpoints foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant at line 3633 returning                     │
│ BinaryOperator::Create(..., Cmp, Cond). This is the first transformation, matching the pattern in the Or-case logic (lines 3615–3635). No prior IR mutation     │
│ happened; thus the failure is directly due to this fold.                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                                                                                         │
│ The transformation assumes Cond and Cmp have identical types. However, LLVM IR permits a scalar condition for vector selects (select i1, <N x T>, <N x T>). In  │
│ that situation, Cond is i1, while Cmp (icmp on vector operands) is <N x i1>. The fold does not account for this mixed scalar/vector case and blindly builds     │
│ (and/or Cmp, Cond), violating the IR type rules for binary operators (both operands must share the same type). The same issue exists for the secondary          │
│ inverted-condition fold (lines 3654–3658). The absence of a type compatibility guard causes the assertion failure. Proper fix: only apply the fold when         │
│ Cond->getType() == Cmp->getType(). Optional enhancement (not required for correctness) would be to broadcast the scalar Cond to a vector, but that would add    │
│ instructions and is outside the intent of a peephole fold.                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points:                                                                                                                                        │
│ Edit Point 1 (lines 3628–3635): Wrap the creation of BinaryOperator in a type check. If types differ, skip the fold (return nullptr path continues). Add a      │
│ comment explaining why the fold is gated (reference PR/reproducer pr119063) to prevent future regressions.                                                      │
│ Suggested replacement logic within the existing if-block:                                                                                                       │
│   Value *Cmp = Builder.CreateICmp(Pred, Other, Constant::getNullValue(Other->getType()));                                                                       │
│   // Only fold if the select condition type matches the compare result type.                                                                                    │
│   // Scalar select condition controlling vector operands (e.g. select i1, <vec>, <vec>)                                                                         │
│   // yields mismatched types (i1 vs <N x i1>) and we cannot form a valid and/or.                                                                                │
│   if (Cmp->getType() == Cond->getType())                                                                                                                        │
│     return BinaryOperator::Create(Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ ? Instruction::And : Instruction::Or, Cmp, Cond);                                                   │
│   // Otherwise, abandon this fold.                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ Edit Point 2 (lines 3654–3658): Apply identical guard for the inverted-condition case (using NotCond instead of Cond). After creating Cmp and NotCond, ensure   │
│ Cmp->getType() == NotCond->getType() before creating BinaryOperator. Add similar explanatory comment.                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ These minimal guards prevent the invalid IR construction without altering existing successful folds.                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The crash is due to missing type compatibility handling when folding icmp patterns involving an 'or' of a select with a scalar condition and vector operands.   │
│ Adding explicit type checks in both transformation branches (easy and inverted cases) avoids generating an invalid binary operator. The fix is conservative,    │
│ preserves all valid folds, and resolves the assertion for the provided reproducer (pr119063).                                                                   │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                                                                                                 │
