  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in InstCombine while folding an icmp with an 'or' instruction (foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant).
The transformation attempts to replace a pattern involving (icmp eq/ne (or (select cond, ...), Other), 0) with a logical AND/OR combining the select condition
(Cond) and a newly created comparison (Cmp). In the provided reproducer, the select condition is a scalar i1 (%cond), while the comparison result is a <4 x i1>
vector (result of icmp between <4 x i32> operands). InstCombine incorrectly tries to create a BinaryOperator (And/Or) with operands of differing types (<4 x i1>
and i1), triggering the assertion S1->getType() == S2->getType().\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows the first mutation attempt happens when visiting the
%cmp instruction. A deferred pattern (%0 = icmp ne <4 x i32> %x, zeroinitializer) indicates InstCombine is attempting to refactor the original icmp. The crash
stack pinpoints foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant at line 3633 returning BinaryOperator::Create(..., Cmp, Cond). This is the first transformation, matching the
pattern in the Or-case logic (lines 3615\u20133635). No prior IR mutation happened; thus the failure is directly due to this fold.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe
transformation assumes Cond and Cmp have identical types. However, LLVM IR permits a scalar condition for vector selects (select i1, <N x T>, <N x T>). In that
situation, Cond is i1, while Cmp (icmp on vector operands) is <N x i1>. The fold does not account for this mixed scalar/vector case and blindly builds (and/or Cmp,
Cond), violating the IR type rules for binary operators (both operands must share the same type). The same issue exists for the secondary inverted-condition fold
(lines 3654\u20133658). The absence of a type compatibility guard causes the assertion failure. Proper fix: only apply the fold when Cond->getType() ==
Cmp->getType(). Optional enhancement (not required for correctness) would be to broadcast the scalar Cond to a vector, but that would add instructions and is
outside the intent of a peephole fold.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points:\nEdit Point 1 (lines 3628\u20133635): Wrap the creation of BinaryOperator in a type check. If
types differ, skip the fold (return nullptr path continues). Add a comment explaining why the fold is gated (reference PR/reproducer pr119063) to prevent future
regressions.\nSuggested replacement logic within the existing if-block:\n  Value *Cmp = Builder.CreateICmp(Pred, Other,
Constant::getNullValue(Other->getType()));\n  // Only fold if the select condition type matches the compare result type.\n  // Scalar select condition controlling
vector operands (e.g. select i1, <vec>, <vec>)\n  // yields mismatched types (i1 vs <N x i1>) and we cannot form a valid and/or.\n  if (Cmp->getType() ==
Cond->getType())\n    return BinaryOperator::Create(Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ ? Instruction::And : Instruction::Or, Cmp, Cond);\n  // Otherwise, abandon this
fold.\n\nEdit Point 2 (lines 3654\u20133658): Apply identical guard for the inverted-condition case (using NotCond instead of Cond). After creating Cmp and
NotCond, ensure Cmp->getType() == NotCond->getType() before creating BinaryOperator. Add similar explanatory comment.\n\nThese minimal guards prevent the invalid
IR construction without altering existing successful folds.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to missing type compatibility handling when folding icmp patterns
involving an 'or' of a select with a scalar condition and vector operands. Adding explicit type checks in both transformation branches (easy and inverted cases)
avoids generating an invalid binary operator. The fix is conservative, preserves all valid folds, and resolves the assertion for the provided reproducer
(pr119063).",
